---

**1. Usage Pattern Analysis**
Overall bandwidth usage is very low, averaging 1.9% of the 10 Mbps provisioned speed. Business hours show slightly higher usage (0.33 Mbps) than off-hours (0.12 Mbps), but both remain minimal. A peak of 12.62 Mbps was recorded, exceeding provisioned speed, but this was an extremely rare and brief event (2 minutes above 90% capacity). Typical sustained daily peaks are around 1.05 Mbps. Usage is stable with a slight downward trend.

**2. Capacity Planning Recommendations**
The current 10 Mbps link is significantly over-provisioned. Average and sustained peak usage are well below 10% of capacity. The 99th percentile usage is 2.32 Mbps, indicating a lower provisioned speed could comfortably support almost all traffic. There is no indication of future growth requiring increased capacity; usage is slightly declining.

**3. Performance Risks & Bottlenecks**
The link performs excellently, operating below 70% capacity 99.98% of the time. While brief bursts of traffic (peak 12.62 Mbps) exceed the provisioned limit, these are extremely rare (0.01% of time above 80% capacity) and do not represent sustained bottlenecks or significant performance risks.

**Conclusion**
The current 10 Mbps link is significantly over-provisioned; consider optimizing capacity to align with actual, consistently low usage.
